        "heading_igqhpi": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "1851: The start of a winemaking legacy",
            "heading_size": "h1"
          }
        },
        "text_MR9Txx": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>In 1851, a group of French missionaries brought with them generations of winemaking knowledge and a few treasured vines to the Hawke’s Bay. Their vision was humble but enduring: to establish a self-sufficient mission that included a vineyard. Through seasons of challenge and change, they cultivated grapes alongside orchards and farmland, continuing the French tradition of wine as part of daily life. Their belief in craft, community, and care for the land became the foundations of Mission Estate’s winemaking philosophy – still present in every bottle today. </p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        },
