        "heading": "Leading the way in New Zealand winemaking",
        "heading_url": "",
        "heading_color": "#002855",
        "text": "In 1871, Brother Cyprien Huchet, arrived at Meeanee. Born in the Loire Valley, he extended the vineyards and changed pruning regimes to improve wine quality. Cyprien also made changes in the cellars by moving production onto a basis that could support commercial sales from 1880s.\n\nThat spirit of innovation continued over the next century. Mission Estate produced the country’s first Méthode Traditionnelle, ‘Fontenella’ in 1963, and in 1983, created New Zealand’s first whole bunch-pressed, barrel-fermented Chardonnay – helping establish Hawke’s Bay as the country’s Chardonnay capital.\n\nIn the 1960s, Brother Joseph Lamb began ground-breaking rootstock research with the Department of Agriculture. Present-day disease-free Sauvignon Blanc, Riesling, Cabernet Sauvignon, Shiraz and Sauvignon rootstocks owe a great deal to this painstaking research work.\n\nThese early ‘firsts’ weren’t just milestones – they helped define an entire industry.",
